Environmental Protection Agency

00:31:18.020 --> 00:31:22.250
led an effort that
came up with 67 draft

00:31:22.250 --> 00:31:25.640
guidelines for credible third
party standards and ecolabels.

00:31:25.640 --> 00:31:29.540
And those guidelines were
divided into four sections.

00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:31.520
So any label that the
federal government

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:35.090
was considering using would have
to meet these 67 guidelines.

00:31:35.090 --> 00:31:37.781
So the first section was how
you develop your standards.

00:31:37.781 --> 00:31:38.780
That's a pretty key one.

00:31:38.780 --> 00:31:40.730
And there are a number
of other standards

00:31:40.730 --> 00:31:43.700
that sort of were embodied
in their questions.

00:31:43.700 --> 00:31:46.550
Then there was a section on
how do you do your verification

00:31:46.550 --> 00:31:48.170
and conformity assessment.

00:31:48.170 --> 00:31:51.950
In some programs the label
who developed the standard

00:31:51.950 --> 00:31:53.300
does the certification.

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:56.540
In some, there are programs
who just develop the standard

00:31:56.540 --> 00:31:59.660
and then other third parties
can do the verification work

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:04.010
provided they meet accreditation
as the certifying body.

00:32:04.010 --> 00:32:07.105
Then the third section was the
credibility of the program.

00:32:07.105 --> 00:32:08.480
Where did they
get their funding?

00:32:08.480 --> 00:32:09.800
Who's on their
board of directors?

00:32:09.800 --> 00:32:11.258
Are there any
conflicts of interest

00:32:11.258 --> 00:32:13.309
in operating the program?

00:32:13.309 --> 00:32:15.350
And then the fourth section,
which is potentially

00:32:15.350 --> 00:32:18.140
the most interesting,
are the standards

00:32:18.140 --> 00:32:19.700
environmentally effective?

00:32:19.700 --> 00:32:22.730
That is, if you buy something
with that ecolabel on it,

00:32:22.730 --> 00:32:24.740
are you actually getting
the benefits that they

00:32:24.740 --> 00:32:26.030
say you're going to get?

00:32:26.030 --> 00:32:29.180
So that speaks to addressing the
key, significant environmental

00:32:29.180 --> 00:32:31.460
impacts and making
sure that it's not

00:32:31.460 --> 00:32:33.509
a label that is sort of
dancing around the edges

00:32:33.509 --> 00:32:35.300
but not hitting to the
heart of the matter.

00:32:35.300 --> 00:32:38.210
So yes, there are standards
and accreditations

00:32:38.210 --> 00:32:40.280
that standard developers
and third party

00:32:40.280 --> 00:32:41.540
certifiers have to meet.

00:32:41.540 --> 00:32:44.360
And these are embodied in
membership requirements

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:46.730
for the Global
Ecolabelling Network.

00:32:46.730 --> 00:32:48.320
In order to join,
you have to prove

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:50.705
that you meet all of those.

00:32:50.705 --> 00:32:53.770
AUDIENCE: I had a question
about forestry certifications.

00:32:53.770 --> 00:32:58.200
So you mentioned it, but just
to make sure I caught it.

00:32:58.200 --> 00:33:02.860
So for like FSC certified wood,
is that part of the Global

00:33:02.860 --> 00:33:04.190
Ecolabelling Network.

00:33:04.190 --> 00:33:05.010
Why or why not?

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:06.540
Or other forestry
certifications.

00:33:06.540 --> 00:33:07.240
MARK PETRUZZI: Right.

00:33:07.240 --> 00:33:07.864
Great question.

00:33:07.864 --> 00:33:09.340
Thank you.

00:33:09.340 --> 00:33:11.710
The GEN member
ecolabels tend to be

00:33:11.710 --> 00:33:15.310
for programs that cover multiple
types of products and services.

00:33:15.310 --> 00:33:17.560
And within the
forestry space, there

00:33:17.560 --> 00:33:21.010
are six, eight or
so labels that just

00:33:21.010 --> 00:33:23.750
certify sustainable
forestry in some way,

00:33:23.750 --> 00:33:26.530
shape, or form whether that's
virgin or post-consumer.

00:33:26.530 --> 00:33:29.920
Some of them actually do put
a certification on products.

00:33:29.920 --> 00:33:32.996
But none of them,
to my knowledge,

00:33:32.996 --> 00:33:35.620
would be able to be a member of
the Global Ecolabelling Network

00:33:35.620 --> 00:33:37.591
because they only
focus on forestry.

00:33:37.591 --> 00:33:40.090
And just like there are labels
that just focus on indoor air

00:33:40.090 --> 00:33:43.919
quality or just focus
on sustainable flooring,

00:33:43.919 --> 00:33:45.460
in order to be a
GEN member, you have

00:33:45.460 --> 00:33:48.880
to have standards for multiple
product and service categories.

00:33:48.880 --> 00:33:52.610
But it is also a really
relevant question,

00:33:52.610 --> 00:33:55.000
because these same
questions about how do they

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:56.209
develop their standards?

00:33:56.209 --> 00:33:58.000
How do they do their
conformity assessment?

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:00.250
Are they addressing the
key impacts of forestry

00:34:00.250 --> 00:34:03.186
within that space of
six or eight labels?

00:34:03.186 --> 00:34:04.810
Some are better than
others, and that's

00:34:04.810 --> 00:34:08.610
been the topic of much debate
in the green building community.

00:34:08.610 --> 00:34:09.719
So, yes.

00:34:09.719 --> 00:34:13.389
And the nice thing about these
key fundamental principles

00:34:13.389 --> 00:34:15.159
is they can apply to
a single attribute

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:19.719
program, a multiple criteria but
applying to a single category

00:34:19.719 --> 00:34:22.570
program, or a type
one ecolabel that

00:34:22.570 --> 00:34:27.020
addresses life cycle across
multiple product categories.

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:28.960
So that's planting
the seeds of these

00:34:28.960 --> 00:34:30.880
are the questions to
be thinking about when

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:34.630
you look behind that
label wherever it fits.

00:34:34.630 --> 00:34:37.550
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about furniture.

00:34:37.550 --> 00:34:41.210
I haven't seen a lot of
ecolabels or see any.

00:34:41.210 --> 00:34:43.260
Maybe I didn't pay
attention enough.

00:34:43.260 --> 00:34:45.300
Can you tell me more
about the furniture?

00:34:45.300 --> 00:34:49.010
Is there an ecolabel for the
office furniture or any type

00:34:49.010 --> 00:34:51.339
of furniture products?

00:34:51.339 --> 00:34:52.130
MARK PETRUZZI: Yes.

00:34:52.130 --> 00:34:54.139
There are a few.

00:34:54.139 --> 00:34:58.280
Many furniture products have
gone through indoor air quality

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:01.790
certification for emissions,
where the chair or the table

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:03.380
is put into a chamber.

00:35:03.380 --> 00:35:05.210
The chamber is closed,
and they actually

00:35:05.210 --> 00:35:08.990
measure what is offgassed in
terms of multiple compounds.

00:35:08.990 --> 00:35:12.590
Greenguard is probably the
most well-known for that.

00:35:12.590 --> 00:35:13.730
But there is also--

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:17.930
for institutional furniture--
the Business and Institutional

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:20.050
Furniture Manufacturers
Association--

00:35:20.050 --> 00:35:23.000
BIFMA-- has a
program called Level

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:26.390
that is for institutional
office furniture.

00:35:26.390 --> 00:35:27.920
And they have
hundreds of products

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:30.270
that have been certified
at three different levels

00:35:30.270 --> 00:35:32.720
in the Level rating system.

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:34.460
But there are some
certifications.

00:35:34.460 --> 00:35:36.980
But most of it is
for institutional

00:35:36.980 --> 00:35:39.620
and office furniture.

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:43.670
There is the Sustainable
Furnishings Association

00:35:43.670 --> 00:35:47.540
for retail furniture that
has some of the furniture

00:35:47.540 --> 00:35:49.300
companies as members.

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:56.000
But that hasn't been as visible
as the BIFMA Level program.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:57.770
But yes, it's a growing
area of concern.

00:35:57.770 --> 00:36:00.520
And also that's a market where--

00:36:00.520 --> 00:36:03.940
in addition to the emissions
from the foam cushions--

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:08.710
things like flame retardants
and brominated compounds

00:36:08.710 --> 00:36:11.230
have been sort of a
campaign-specific thing

00:36:11.230 --> 00:36:14.330
because these products are
used in schools and offices.

00:36:14.330 --> 00:36:18.200
And we're exposed to them
a lot of hours of the day.

00:36:18.200 --> 00:36:20.140
AUDIENCE: You mentioned funding.

00:36:20.140 --> 00:36:24.230
And I'd be really concerned
if the people getting

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:27.040
the certifications paid for it.

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:28.540
But at the same
time, I know there's

00:36:28.540 --> 00:36:30.470
no way that I could pay for it.

00:36:30.470 --> 00:36:34.570
So what's the current thinking
around seemingly hard to solve

00:36:34.570 --> 00:36:35.900
problem?

00:36:35.900 --> 00:36:37.660
MARK PETRUZZI: Some
of the GEN members

00:36:37.660 --> 00:36:40.420
are government-sponsored
programs.

00:36:40.420 --> 00:36:44.200
So there is some endowment
and funding coming from that.

00:36:44.200 --> 00:36:46.720
Some of them do take
a fee for service

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:50.060
where there is a fee for
getting the certification.

00:36:50.060 --> 00:36:53.770
And this is why the question
about the accreditation for how

00:36:53.770 --> 00:36:55.900
they operate is so important.

00:36:55.900 --> 00:36:59.343
Usually it's a fee-- the same
fee charged to everybody--

00:37:01.870 --> 00:37:02.600
initially.

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:04.180
And then there may
be a license fee

00:37:04.180 --> 00:37:05.950
that's based on the
sales of the product.

00:37:05.950 --> 00:37:09.821
So if you sold 100 products,
at the end of that term of 12

00:37:09.821 --> 00:37:11.320
months or whatever
the term was, you

00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:13.750
would owe a fee for the use
of the Ecolabel on that.

00:37:13.750 --> 00:37:16.180
So unfortunately,
fees are definitely

00:37:16.180 --> 00:37:18.730
a part of it to keep the
organization running.

00:37:18.730 --> 00:37:21.880
But then for a lot of
the nonprofit labels--

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:26.347
because of the 501(c)(3)
IRS tax classification--

00:37:26.347 --> 00:37:28.930
they're not allowed to have any
direct financial relationship.

00:37:28.930 --> 00:37:32.170
So they may just charge
a flat fee and that's

00:37:32.170 --> 00:37:34.124
irrespective of how
many units actually

00:37:34.124 --> 00:37:35.290
get sold in the marketplace.

00:37:35.290 --> 00:37:38.290
So whether the company sells
one or they sell one million,

00:37:38.290 --> 00:37:41.290
the fee is an evaluation fee
to determine whether or not

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:43.420
you meet the standard and
get the certification.

00:37:43.420 --> 00:37:46.269
But it's not directly linked
to the success of that product

00:37:46.269 --> 00:37:47.060
in the marketplace.

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:51.218
So there are a variety of
different funding models.

00:37:51.218 --> 00:37:54.880
and it is a challenge because
the marketplace really

00:37:54.880 --> 00:37:57.130
needs to show the value for
this in the business case.

00:37:57.130 --> 00:37:59.494
And the business case
is often the companies

00:37:59.494 --> 00:38:01.660
see that marketing benefit
of having the third party

00:38:01.660 --> 00:38:02.680
certification.

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:05.200
So paying for it helps
to keep the lights on

00:38:05.200 --> 00:38:07.360
and the doors open
for the ecolabel.

00:38:07.360 --> 00:38:09.370
AUDIENCE: So there
was a slide where

00:38:09.370 --> 00:38:13.340
you showed all different
ecolabels, not all of them

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:18.100
part of GEN. As a
consumer, most consumers

00:38:18.100 --> 00:38:20.270
aren't super knowledgeable
of what ecolabels

00:38:20.270 --> 00:38:24.340
are part of GEN.
Is there a trend

00:38:24.340 --> 00:38:28.690
that it's going to become
more easy for consumers

00:38:28.690 --> 00:38:33.370
to know what valid
ecolabels are or how--

00:38:33.370 --> 00:38:35.320
Because most consumers
wouldn't spend time

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:38.050
to research all the
different ecolabels

00:38:38.050 --> 00:38:39.400
before going to the store.

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:40.026
Right?

00:38:40.026 --> 00:38:40.900
MARK PETRUZZI: Right.

00:38:40.900 --> 00:38:42.066
And that's a great question.

00:38:42.066 --> 00:38:44.060
And that's part of why
this education campaign

00:38:44.060 --> 00:38:47.540
and having the first annual
World Ecolabel Day is something

00:38:47.540 --> 00:38:48.540
that GEN thought of.

00:38:48.540 --> 00:38:53.980
Because yes, even people like me
that have been immersed in this

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:56.680
don't study all
463 on the website.

00:38:56.680 --> 00:39:00.280
But I've got the tools if I see
something at the grocery store

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:02.200
that I haven't seen
before, I'll whip out

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:03.400
my phone I'll start looking.

00:39:03.400 --> 00:39:03.899
OK.

00:39:03.899 --> 00:39:06.880
What is this green tree logo
that I've never seen before?

00:39:06.880 --> 00:39:10.520
And usually within a few
clicks on that mobile website

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:12.140
I can-- oh, at
the bottom it says

00:39:12.140 --> 00:39:14.740
funded by the such and
such industry association.

00:39:14.740 --> 00:39:18.040
Or I can see that
we at Company X

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:21.071
think this is our company
environmental program.

00:39:21.071 --> 00:39:23.320
We put this on all our
products to show our commitment

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:24.111
to the environment.

00:39:24.111 --> 00:39:26.620
So you can tease
out pretty quickly

00:39:26.620 --> 00:39:29.162
if it's a credible label
or not, but it is going

00:39:29.162 --> 00:39:30.370
to take a little bit of work.

00:39:30.370 --> 00:39:34.300
And without somebody coming in
and policing the marketplace,

00:39:34.300 --> 00:39:37.360
the EPA effort to identify
the good ones for use

00:39:37.360 --> 00:39:39.340
in federal procurement,
Google's efforts

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:42.520
by being an affiliate member of
GEN to say, hey, as a company,

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:44.440
we only want to
use ecolabels that

00:39:44.440 --> 00:39:46.330
meet our strict guidelines.

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:47.530
That sends a signal.

00:39:47.530 --> 00:39:50.560
But it also, for the
time being, requires

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:52.810
consumers taking a
little bit of effort

00:39:52.810 --> 00:39:59.112
to determine whether or
not that smells fishy.

00:39:59.112 --> 00:40:03.880
AUDIENCE: And do you all have
an app or anything like that?

00:40:03.880 --> 00:40:04.630
MARK PETRUZZI: No.

00:40:04.630 --> 00:40:06.171
I don't think the
Global Ecolabelling

00:40:06.171 --> 00:40:08.290
Network has an app yet.

00:40:08.290 --> 00:40:10.765
That's probably on their
wish list for funding.

00:40:10.765 --> 00:40:12.850
AUDIENCE: Just curious
about your knowledge

00:40:12.850 --> 00:40:14.350
of the prevalence
of fraud with some

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:15.335
of these certified products.

00:40:15.335 --> 00:40:16.751
I was working on
a startup before.

00:40:16.751 --> 00:40:20.197
We were looking into
organic agriculture fraud.

00:40:20.197 --> 00:40:22.780
There have been large scandals
with some products people tried

00:40:22.780 --> 00:40:24.940
to pass off as
certified organic.

00:40:24.940 --> 00:40:26.650
But curious about
the other products,

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:28.339
as well, how prevalent that is.

00:40:28.339 --> 00:40:29.630
MARK PETRUZZI: It is a problem.

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:32.080
And that's one of
the 67 guidelines

00:40:32.080 --> 00:40:34.020
that I mentioned that
EPA had put forth--

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:37.570
and even in the ISO standard
and the GEN requirements--

00:40:37.570 --> 00:40:41.740
policing and enforcing your
ecolabel is super important.

00:40:41.740 --> 00:40:43.840
And all the time I
spend at Green Seal,

00:40:43.840 --> 00:40:46.420
a big portion of that
was spent on enforcement.

00:40:46.420 --> 00:40:50.630
And having the products that
are Green Seal certified listed

00:40:50.630 --> 00:40:53.540
on our website was the
first step in that.

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:57.010
Because consumers, especially
the institutional purchasers--

00:40:57.010 --> 00:40:59.080
a company would come
in and make a pitch.

00:40:59.080 --> 00:41:00.500
We'd like you to
buy our product.

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:02.390
We're Green Seal
certified-- they would

00:41:02.390 --> 00:41:03.930
verify that on our website.

00:41:03.930 --> 00:41:06.410
And if it wasn't on our website,
we would get a phone call.

00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:08.191
Hey, Company X was
just in my office.

00:41:08.191 --> 00:41:09.440
They said they were certified.

00:41:09.440 --> 00:41:11.240
I can't find them
on your website.

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:13.700
Now sometimes they
were just super excited

00:41:13.700 --> 00:41:15.440
we hadn't posted it
on the website yet.

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:17.780
So they were
legitimately certified.

00:41:17.780 --> 00:41:20.150
But maybe they were
but two years ago.

00:41:20.150 --> 00:41:22.040
And we terminated
their certification,

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:24.680
but they had an old
paper with the old logo

00:41:24.680 --> 00:41:26.510
or something on it.

00:41:26.510 --> 00:41:29.180
So yes, there are
requirements that the mark has

00:41:29.180 --> 00:41:32.450
to be legally protected,
registered as a certification

00:41:32.450 --> 00:41:36.380
mark, that you do have to take
steps to police and enforce it.

00:41:36.380 --> 00:41:38.120
Usually that hierarchy
would be something

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:40.100
like they would get
a phone call from me.

00:41:40.100 --> 00:41:42.860
If that didn't work, they would
get a phone call or a letter

00:41:42.860 --> 00:41:43.767
from our CEO.

00:41:43.767 --> 00:41:46.100
If that didn't work, then
they would get a lovely letter

00:41:46.100 --> 00:41:48.740
from a four name
law firm saying,

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:51.320
you are using a registered
certification mark

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:52.370
without license.

00:41:52.370 --> 00:41:53.930
Cease and desist or else.

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:55.790
And sometimes it came to that.

00:41:55.790 --> 00:42:00.440
We would even police and enforce
registration of domain names.

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:05.690
Because a manufacturer having
Green Seal dot whatever,

00:42:05.690 --> 00:42:08.120
that wasn't actually Green
Seal, but was somehow

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:10.340
promoting their products
or leading people

00:42:10.340 --> 00:42:13.580
to think under that
pretense that they were.

00:42:13.580 --> 00:42:15.580
That's a misuse of
our name and mark.

00:42:15.580 --> 00:42:17.557
So yes, it's a
never-ending battle.

00:42:17.557 --> 00:42:19.390
Yes, some of them are
going to slip through.

00:42:19.390 --> 00:42:23.240
But every time I read one
of those I'm like you.

00:42:23.240 --> 00:42:24.570
I think, oh, that's not great.

00:42:24.570 --> 00:42:26.420
But it's great that
it comes to light

00:42:26.420 --> 00:42:29.360
so they can hopefully implement
better controls over it.

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:33.110
And it speaks to the value that
companies want to misuse it

00:42:33.110 --> 00:42:36.680
because they know they will
be able to sell more or reach

00:42:36.680 --> 00:42:39.630
a target audience that--
if they don't have it--

00:42:39.630 --> 00:42:41.250
they may not be able to sell to.

00:42:41.250 --> 00:42:43.700
So it shows that
there's a value for it.

00:42:43.700 --> 00:42:47.180
But yes, eternal
vigilance is the price

00:42:47.180 --> 00:42:48.500
of ecolabelling I guess.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:50.560
SPEAKER: Thank you, again, Mark.

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:52.310
And thank you everyone
for your questions.

00:42:52.310 --> 00:42:53.360
We really appreciate your time.

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:54.230
So let give it up for Mark.

